# 11. Domain Invariants

The Integration domain shall always satisfy the following architectural
invariants.

## 11.1 Single Responsibility

Integration is responsible only for introducing trusted operational
information into the cognitive architecture.

It shall never perform:

- Observation
- Correlation
- Root Cause Analysis
- Prediction
- Decision Making
- Learning

These responsibilities belong to downstream domains.

---

## 11.2 Immutable Publication

Once a Signal has been published it becomes immutable.

Corrections shall generate a new Signal rather than modifying the previous
publication.

This guarantees:

- Traceability
- Auditability
- Explainability

throughout the cognitive lifecycle.

---

## 11.3 Technology Independence

Integration responsibilities are independent of:

- OpenTelemetry
- Prometheus
- Datadog
- Splunk
- Elastic
- Dynatrace
- CloudWatch
- Azure Monitor
- Grafana
- Kafka
- RabbitMQ

These are implementation technologies rather than architectural concepts.

---

## 11.4 Canonical Representation

Every published Signal shall conform to the canonical information model.

Vendor-specific formats shall not propagate beyond the Integration domain.

---

## 11.5 Trusted Inputs

Only validated information may enter the cognitive architecture.

Information failing validation shall be rejected, quarantined, or marked
invalid according to runtime policy.

---

# 12. Quality Attributes

The Integration domain emphasizes the following quality attributes.

## Accuracy

Signals shall faithfully represent external operational information.

---

## Freshness

Signals should be published with minimal delay after acquisition.

---

## Reliability

Temporary failures in external systems shall not compromise architectural
integrity.

---

## Scalability

Integration shall support thousands of heterogeneous operational resources.

---

## Extensibility

New source types should be added through adapters or plugins without changing
architectural responsibilities.

---

## Traceability

Every Signal should be traceable to:

- Original source
- Acquisition time
- Resource
- Collection mechanism
- Validation outcome

---

# 13. Domain Interactions

The Integration domain interacts with only two architectural boundaries.

## Upstream

External operational environment.

Examples:

- Kubernetes
- Linux
- Windows
- AWS
- Azure
- GCP
- VMware
- Databases
- Applications
- Network Devices

---

## Downstream

Observe Domain

Integration publishes Signals.

Observe consumes Signals.

No other architectural dependency exists.

```
External Systems
        │
        ▼
+------------------+
|   Integration    |
+------------------+
        │
        ▼
+------------------+
|     Observe      |
+------------------+
```

---

# 14. Architectural Rationale

Separating Integration from Observe is one of the most important architectural
decisions within OpsiMind.

Many monitoring platforms combine collection and interpretation into a single
component.

OpsiMind deliberately separates them.

This provides several benefits.

## Separation of Facts from Interpretation

Integration publishes facts.

Observe interprets facts.

Keeping these concerns separate prevents semantic leakage between domains.

---

## Vendor Independence

Operational sources continuously evolve.

By introducing canonical Signals, downstream domains remain insulated from
vendor-specific schemas and protocols.

---

## Replaceable Integrations

New technologies can be supported by implementing additional acquisition
adapters without changing the cognitive architecture.

---

## Consistent Cognitive Pipeline

Every cognitive process begins from the same trusted information model,
regardless of the original operational environment.

---

